    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bab6814e_2be91615",
        "filename": "docs/monasca-api-spec.md",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 506,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-05-19T16:18:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I looked up the definition of deterministic a while ago, when you first proposed this term, because most people think that deterministic has to do with randomness. There are several definitions. The only one that fits is from, http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/deterministic,  \"the quality or state of being determined\". \n\nThe way that you\u0027ve described this is that deterministic alarms can end up in the UNDETERMINED state, which is completely opposite to the definition from merriam-webster, where deterministic is the state of being determined. Stating something is deterministic and then giving it the UNDETERMINED state is really confusing. I asked several folks on the team here what they thought, and they validated what I was thinking too. \n\nI think we should change this to the opposite sense.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 506,
        "startChar": 23,
        "endLine": 506,
        "endChar": 24
      },
      "revId": "f021980351890e469f61c2bdc1a3326f64d55d11",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
